english:
  title: A Letter of Admonition to My Descendants Written During Illness
  author: Jeong Gyu
  language: eng
  text: |-
    To teach children, one must employ righteous guidance. To serve parents, nothing surpasses the practice of propriety. Thus do I set forth my enduring commands, offering instruction to my worthy heirs.

    I have long observed how the common folk, upon losing their parents, abandon the true intent behind the sage's establishment of ritual. Instead, they follow the empty words of Buddhist salvation, wastefully performing seven-day mourning rites and extending their lamentation for three months before burial. The world drifts with the current, oblivious; people, unenlightened, compete in their haste. As propriety fades from view, the eternal principles of human relations crumble. This affliction has troubled me for years—hear my words and take them to heart.

    Though my years may yet be many, what remedy against persistent illness? Alas, how can I linger long in this world? My only fear is that the western mountains draw near. Should sudden calamity strike, do not seek refuge in the Three Treasures. Zhu Xi left behind arguments against such practices, unmarred by a thousand years. Confucius demonstrated the way of non-transgression, imperishable through ten thousand generations. As for the distinction between heaven and hell—said to be the reward of good and evil—even if a judge presides, surely without partiality. How much less could your hasty offerings influence what my lifetime conduct could not achieve? Consider: when breath gathers, form solidifies and nature is complete; when breath disperses, the earthly spirit descends and the heavenly soul ascends. This principle is luminous—any person can grasp it. How then could one dead in this world be reborn in that?

    Therefore I charge you: attend carefully to my words. To find joy in poverty is what the virtuous do not reject. To let the dead injure the living is what sages forbid. Do not grieve excessively so as to destroy your nature. Do not indulge in lavish burial to deceive the world. Do not be confused by theories of feng shui and orientation. Do not follow superstitions about metal and fire taboos. Simply ensure proper placement—why speak of fortune and misfortune being bound to such things? Weigh the ancient and modern, and follow what is fitting. Measure wealth and poverty, and conduct ritual accordingly.

    Alas, to meet death while upright—what more could I ask? But to act contrary to propriety—how could you call that filial? Do not abandon this command. Preserve it eternally for your descendants.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Zhu Xi (朱熹): The influential Neo-Confucian philosopher who argued against Buddhist and Daoist funeral practices, advocating a return to classical Confucian ritual.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Three Treasures (三寶): Buddhist term referring to Buddha, dharma, and sangha—the author warns against Buddhist religious practices at funerals.'
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to 'western mountains' is a poetic way of indicating approaching death, drawing on classical Chinese literary conventions.
